At 21:51 20/09/2004, you wrote:
&gt;Would it be accurate to say that TWEANs are a subset of the GP domain?
&gt;e.g. each neuron is a node that applies a function, but there happens to
&gt;be only one function (in most cases), whereas in GP there is a llibrary
&gt;of different functions. If you gift your TWEAN with a range of
&gt;activation functions then the lines between the two domains become even
&gt;more blurred. From the posts so far I take it that GP&#39;s evolve tree
&gt;structures, whereas neural nets tend to have, well,  interconnected
&gt;networks of nodes. But are the two approaches really that different?

They&#39;re not _all_ that different, but there&#39;s some differences of history, 
attitude etc etc.

I would not say it was true that TWEANs are a subset of GP, I would say 
that TWEANs are analogous to a subset of GP.

Is that useful?  The resemblance is sufficient to be interesting...

